tion scholarship, where adapters are interpreters as well as creators, this study will look at how Agatha Christie is closer to Gothic horror than what we realise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHorror television programs. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 4aRadio and Television. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aAgatha Christie, crime fiction, horror, gothic, adaptations, televisuality.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048556649?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048556649423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048556649/original  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles